RocketPool
Security Review
Contents
1 Introduction
1.1 About Cantina
1.2 Disclaimer
1.3 Risk assessment
1.3.1 Severity Classification
2 Security Review Summary
Issues Found
2.1 Scope
3 Findings
3.1 Critical Risk
3.1.1 Malicious node operators can add validators with reused pubkeys to drain user capital
3.1.2 Linked list data structure in LinkedListStorage can be corrupted
3.2 High Risk

3.2.1 Implementation of EIP-7782 changing assumed block time of 12 seconds will cause protocol-
wide issues

3.2.2 Incorrect/repeated withdrawal from rocketSmoothingPool in executeRewardSnapshot()
will lead to loss of ETH rewards
3.2.3 Missing contracts from the RocketUpgradeOneDotFour upgrade contract
3.2.4 Allowing extra upper bits for indexes allows invalid proofs to pass in BeaconStateVerifier
3.3 Medium Risk

3.3.1 Missing lower guardrail for reduced.bond may allow validators to stake with lower bond
than expected

3.3.2 Missing guardrails for upgradeveto.quorum and upgrade.delay can affect protocol up-
grades
3.3.3 Node Operator can perpetually lock a third-party depositor funds
3.3.4 Mix-up between list and vector types in the SSZ library
3.4 Low Risk
3.4.1 Use of incorrect/repeated ABIs will lead to integration errors
3.4.2 Missed exit challenges by oDAO will lead to loss of user capital
3.4.3 Two compromised oDAO members could collude to temporarily prevent reward distributions
3.4.4 challengeExit() allows less than intended challenges
3.4.5 Megapool MEV theft penalties can be applied multiple times per block with different amounts
3.4.6 Minipool MEV theft penalties will not be applied at 51% consensus threshold

3.4.7 Missing forced distribution before changed capital ratio scenarios causes incorrect accrued
staking rewards distribution

3.4.8 Allowing distribute() to be called before the first staked validator may cause inaccuracy
in rewards distribution
3.4.9 Missing upper guardrail on notify_threshold allows all exiting validators to be penalized
3.4.10 Incorrect operator prevents the application of the maximum allowed late notification fine
3.4.11 Missing conditional check for exit challenge creation deviates from RPIP-72 specification

3.4.12 Missing lower guardrail on late.notify.fine allows exiting validators to never incur any
late notification fine
3.4.13 Compromised oDAO can apply MEV theft penalty to arbitrary validators
Recommendation: Consider:

3.4.14 Missing upper guardrail on maximum.megapool.eth.penalty allows validators to be arbi-
trarily penalized for MEV theft

3.4.15 Outdated implementation of >= 2 days lower guardrail for
megapool.time.before.dissolve deviates from specification

3.4.16 Outdated rationale for minipool.maximum.penalty.count may allow oDAO to dispropor-
tionately penalize untransitioned minipools
However:

3.4.17 Missing upper guardrail on minipool.maximum.penalty.count allows validators to be
arbitrarily penalized for MEV theft

3.4.18 Missing guardrails for network.reth.collateral.target may affect redemptions and
staking

3.4.19 Missing upper guardrail for network.submit.balances.frequency may prevent timely
network balance updates
3.4.20 RPL price update frequency is never enforced on oDAO

3.4.21 Missing guardrails for node.unstaking.period can cause unexpected withdrawal behav-
iors

3.4.22 Missing upper guardrail for node.voting.power.stake.maximum allows bypass of RPL
clamping to increase voting power
3.4.23 Security Council proposals will pass at 50% member quorum threshold
3.4.24 A single compromised Security Council member can veto an upgrade proposal
Recommendation: Consider:

3.4.25 Upgrade delay of 7 days may be insufficient given the current validator exit queue wait
times

3.4.26 Setting network.submit.prices.enabled is incorrectly implemented as SC changeable
parameter without delay
3.4.27 Missing guardrails for members.rplbond allows current members to manipulate oDAO
3.4.28 Missing guardrails for oDAO challenge times may make the challenge process ineffective

3.4.29 Missing guardrails on members.challenge.cost allow members to prevent non-member
challenges or allow spamming
3.4.30 Missing guardrails on oDAO voting settings can make the proposal voting process ineffective
3.4.31 Missing check allows challenged members to refute beyond the challenge window
3.4.32 Missing check allows a challenge proposer to also later remove the challenged member
3.4.33 getQueueTop() returns an incorrect validator

3.4.34 Missing upper guardrail for megapool.time.before.dissolve can prevent validators from
being dissolved
3.4.35 Unchecked state transition may lead to unexpected behavior in setUseLatestDelegate()
3.4.36 Missing sanity check for _stakingEth <= _totalEth could cause unexpected behavior
3.4.37 Allowing pDAO to control voter share of revenue is risky
3.4.38 Nodes can withdraw ETH or credits even if they have outstanding protocol debt

3.4.39 Missed deletion of pending withdrawal address allows a potentially untrusted one to set
itself as withdrawal address
Scenario of concern:
3.4.40 Incorrect uint64 casts in RocketDepositPool.getQueueTop()
3.4.41 Missing onlyThisLatestContract modifier for functions in RocketDepositPool
3.4.42 Improvements for BeaconStateVerifier and the SSZ library
3.5 Gas Optimization
3.5.1 Gas optimizations
3.6 Informational
3.6.1 RocketMegapoolManager functions can make arbitrary external calls

3.6.2 Hardcoding consensus threshold for Megapool penalty enforcement prevents any required
modification
3.6.3 Specification of lower guardrail for Megapool MEV theft penalty is contradicting
3.6.4 Avoid hardcoding the gas amount passed to the sha256 precompile
3.6.5 Unused code reduces readability
3.6.6 Excess caller privileges provided in function access control is risky
Examples are:
3.6.7 Missing sanity checks could cause unexpected behavior
3.6.8 Use of pragma abicoder v2 is unnecessary
3.6.9 Not using leading underscore for private/internal function names reduces readability

3.6.10 Resetting validator.expressUsed and validator.lastAssignmentTime will avoid stale
values
